note: Narrow CME seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. Source may be opening field lines seen on the NE limb in SDO AIA 171 starting at about 2025-08-25T23:34Z. These field lines appear to trace down to approx. N30E60, but may also be from beyond the NE limb.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2.

cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2) and confirmed by the location of the source - the flare somewhat eastward of the location of AR 14199.

note: CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. Ejecta can be seen in STEREO A EUVI 304, SDO AIA 304, and GOES SUVI 304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Preliminary triangulated fit using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2.

note: Narrow flux rope CME seen to the ENE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. Source is likely a minor eruption and M1.0 flare peaking at 2025-08-26T07:22Z from N00E80 (no AR yet), best seen in SDO AIA 171.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.

note: Slow, large-scale streamer blowout associated with transport of magnetic flux and field lines above the active region complex in the southeast near AR 14197 (S17E45) with notable southward deflection best seen in GOES SUVI 284 starting as early as around 2025-08-26T11:00Z; by 16:00Z, most of the magnetic field lines have disappeared from the southeast limb as the CME propagates out of the field of view.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement of the leading edge using triangulation between SOHO C2, C3 and STEREO A COR2A.

note: CME first seen to the East in STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-08-26T14:09Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. Opening field lines can be seen in SDO AIA 171 and 193, along with post eruptive arcades visible in SDO AIA 94.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1.

note: High northern latitude CME with the significantly narrower, brighter bulk and a much fainter broader shock, seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2. cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2) and confirmed by what we know about the likely far-sided source from coronal signatures - moving field lines in SDO AIA 171 and an ejecta from behind the NE limb in SDO AIA 304.

note: Faint loop CME to the SW in all coronagraphs. Start time can be a bit earlier: the CME is not clearly seen in the early timestamps of SOHO LASCO C2. No clear source found for it in EUV imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1).  No source has been found for this CME in available EUV imagery.

note: Narrow CME first seen to the NE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-08-26T21:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a minor eruption seen located at approx. N05E60 beginning at approx. 2025-08-26T20:32Z. This eruption can be seen exhibiting a Northern deflection in SDO AIA 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1.

note: Faint narrow CME with a fuzzy front directed S (maybe SSW) in SOHO C2 and GOES CCOR-1 and to the SSE in COR2A. Followed by many outflows. No clear source was found in EUV imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: A super uncertain analysis based on the fit of the very fuzzy faint front with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2). The source has not been found in EUV imagery.

note: This CME is visible to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Not seen in GOES CCOR-1. The source is likely related to field line movement visible over the northeast limb in SDO AIA 171 imagery starting around 2025-08-27T01:00Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: Faint high southern latitude CME/outflow with a fuzzy front, following the earlier (also very faint) CME: 2025-08-27T00:36Z. No source has been found in EUV imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate analysis based on the fit with SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs. No source has been found for this event to confirm this analysis.

note: Narrow CME to the NNE in all 3 coronagraphs. No source found in EUV imagery, except for maybe some movement of field lines on/close to NE limb in SDO AIA 171 near the start of the CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2); not confirmed by a source as no clear source found in EUV imagery.

note: Faint CME seen to the West in STEREO A COR2 only. Not visible in GOES CCOR-1. Ongoing data gap in SOHO LASCO which started at 2025-08-27T12:30Z. There is some uncertainty with the source, but the strongest candidate is a possible partial filament eruption seen on the STEREO A West limb (W136 in HEEQ longitude) in STEREO A EUVI 304 around 2025-08-27T10:45Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement using STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: Faint CME seen to the East in STEREO A COR2 only. Not visible in GOES CCOR-1. Ongoing data gap in SOHO LASCO which started at 2025-08-27T12:30Z. Source may be some possible opening field lines seen at about N05 on the East limb of STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery, specifically between frames 2025-08-27T10:15-10:45Z of STEREO A EUVI 304. This is from near AR 14199 (N05E53). There is a small post-eruptive loop seen at AR 14199 at 2025-08-27T10:36Z in SDO AIA 131, but no other notable eruptive signatures in other SDO AIA wavelengths.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on candidate source location using STEREO A COR2 frames only. Not visible in CCOR-1 due to faintness. Not captured by SOHO LASCO due to a data gap which began 2025-08-27T12:30Z.

note: Faint flux rope CME seen to the Southeast in STEREO A COR2 and South in GOES CCOR-1. Source is uncertain; there is no clear source in available UV imagery of the disk. Not captured by SOHO LASCO due to a data gap which began 2025-08-27T12:30Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1. Not captured by SOHO LASCO due to a data gap which began 2025-08-27T12:30Z.

note: Faint, irregular CME seen to the SSE in GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2. Source is uncertain, but may possibly be gradually opening field lines near AR 14201 (S21E45) as well as AR 14202 (S15E52) and AR 14197 (S17E32) seen starting around 2025-08-27T15:30Z in SDO AIA 171. cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1. Not captured by SOHO LASCO due to a data gap which began 2025-08-27T12:30Z.

note: This CME is visible to the south in STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. It is not observed in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery due to a data gap from 2025-08-27T12:24Z to 2025-08-28T07:12Z. The source is unknown and may be far-sided as there are no clear source signatures on the Earth-facing disk around the time of this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery.

note: CME seen as a narrow flux rope CME to the NE in STEREO A COR2 and as an extremely faint and wider flux rope to the NNE in GOES CCOR-1. Source is a small eruption seen starting at 2025-08-27T20:02Z seen as brightening from AR 14198 (N10E09) and post-eruptive brightening seen surrounding the Active Region in SDO AIA 131/304. Not captured in real time by SOHO LASCO due to a data gap which began 2025-08-27T12:30Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1. Leading edge is extremely faint in GOES CCOR-1, adding some uncertainty to the measurement. Not captured in real time by SOHO LASCO due to a data gap which began 2025-08-27T12:30Z.

note: This CME is visible to the north/northeast in STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. It is not observed in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 imagery due to a data gap from 2025-08-27T12:24Z to 2025-08-28T07:12Z. The source is likely far-sided and related to an eruption observed over the northeast limb starting around 2025-08-28T01:09Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. A subsequent opening of field lines can be observed over the northeast limb in SDO AIA 171, 193, and GOES SUVI 284 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. This measurement is speculative as the source is likely far-sided, but a far-sided fit was difficult to obtain.

note: This CME is visible to the east/northeast in GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely related to an eruption on the northeast limb (centered around N15E90) starting around 2025-08-28T06:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: This CME has a diffuse leading edge but can be observed to the west in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures on the Earth-facing disk around the time of this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. As the source is far-sided and a precise source location is unknown, the measured parameters may vary slightly.

note: Faint loop to the N/NE in STEREO A COR2, partially blocked by pylon in GOES CCOR-1 and mostly covered by a data gap in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Its source is a large northern filament eruption centered near N50W30 but extending even more to the NE, which begins to lift-off around 2025-08-28T08:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: A very approximate analysis based on the fit of this very faint front with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). There seems to be an eastward deflection from the more western source going on.

note: This CME is visible to the south in STEREO A COR2 and to the southwest in GOES CCOR-1 imagery. The source is likely an eruption centered near S33W50 starting around 2025-08-28T11:00Z as seen in SDO AIA 131, 171, 193, 304 imagery. An opening of field lines can be observed over the southwest limb in SDO AIA 171 and 193 imagery around this time. Additionally, dimming can be observed south of the eruption site in SDO AIA 193 with post eruptive arcades visible starting around 2025-08-28T12:15Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the approximate source location and best fit between STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery.

note: Narrow flux rope CME seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1 and to the SE in STEREO A COR2. Source may be some subtle opening field lines with strong southern deflection seen from AR 14197 (S20E20) around 2025-08-28T18:05Z in STEREO A EUVI 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.

note: Wide flux rope CME seen to the NE in GOES CCOR-1 and to the NW in STEREO A COR2. Seen in one frame of SOHO LASCO C2 so far due to regularly scheduled downlink data gap. Source is a far-sided eruption, seen as field line movement and a liftoff of material from beyond the N limb as seen in SDO AIA 171 starting at 2025-08-28T19:06Z. A far-sided eruption can also be seen beyond the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI . Brightening can be seen just beyond the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI 304 at 2025-08-28T19:45Z and opening field lines can be seen further north and beyond the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI 193 imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1. This CME was captured by only one frame of SOHO LASCO C2 in real time, due to a regularly scheduled downlink data gap which began 2025-08-28T20:24Z.

note: Faint CME with diffuse narrow leading edge seen to the NE in STEREO A COR2, GOES CCOR-1, and SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Source is an eruption on the NE limb seen as brightening at N19E85 and narrowly opening field lines starting at 2025-08-28T20:24Z in SDO AIA 171.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of GOES CCOR-1 and a few frames of STEREO A COR2. The leading edge is extremely diffuse, adding some uncertainty to this measurement. This CME was captured by only one frame of SOHO LASCO C2 in real time, due to a regularly scheduled downlink data gap which began 2025-08-28T20:24Z.

note: Faint less than 10 degree half width CME observed to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only. The source is a small filament eruption in SDO AIA 304 from AR 14188 starting at 2025-08-29T02:03Z, filament ejecta centered around S12W65.

cmeAnalyses.note: Single spacecraft 3D measurement with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only due to lack of visibility in other coronagraphs, and the observed source around S12W65. Longitude could vary W60-W70. Half width less than 10 degrees.

note: Faint less than 10 degree half width CME observed to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 only. The source is a small filament eruption in SDO AIA 304 from AR 14188 starting at 2025-08-29T13:51Z, filament ejecta centered around S12W75.

cmeAnalyses.note: Single spacecraft 3D measurement with SOHO LASCO C2 only due to lack of visibility in other coronagraphs, and the observed source around S12W75. Longitude could vary W70-W80. Half width less than 10 degrees.

The early propagation in LASCO C3 is missed in real time due to a regularly scheduled downlink data gap in SOHO LASCO. The source of this CME is most likely a far-sided filament eruption seen in STA EUVI 304. The filament appears to lift off the disk around 2025-08-29T15:45Z but can be seen slowly rising for several hours prior to the eruption.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best-fit among SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 as well as a visible source signature beyond the limb from STEREO A.

note: Faint CME first visible to the E in GOES CCOR-1 starting around 2025-08-29T20:00Z. This CME in only visible in GOES CCOR-1 and is covered by data gaps in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. This CME fades after only a few frames. There is no definitive source, but there is some continuous minor activity on the eastern limb that could be a source possibility.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very uncertain, five frame plane-of-sky measurement based only on GOES CCOR-1.

note: Narrow jet CME seen to the ENE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Source may be subtle field line movement seen near AR 14106 (N10E75) around 2025-08-29T19:28Z in SDO AIA 171. This CME is not discernable in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to both a data gap in STEREO A COR2 which lasted from 2025-08-29T18:38Z to 2025-08-29T21T21:23Z and the faintness of the leading edge.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement using candidate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 frames.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. No clear source is observed on-disk here, but good confidence in the coronagraph triangulation on front-sided parameters near E78.

note: CME first seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-08-29T22:12Z. CME is also seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The CME fades before leaving the FOV of C2 and is easier to see in running difference imagery. There is not a good, discernible source candidate for this CME on the Earth-facing disk, so the source is possibly far-sided.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best-fit among SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. There is some uncertainty in this measurement due to the faintness of the front and lack of good source candidate.

note: Faint loop CME seen to the NE in STEREO A COR2 and as an extremely faint flux rope CME to the NNW in SOHO LASCO C2. Not visible in CCOR-1; obstructed by pylon. Source is an eruption from AR 14198 (N11W19) seen as dimming and brightening starting at 2025-08-29T23:37Z in SDO AIA 193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. Not visible in CCOR-1; obstructed by pylon.

note: Faint CME observed to the far NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2, less than 10 degree half width and fades quickly. Not observed in GOES CCOR-1 due to earthshine obscuring the coronagraph at this time. The source is not well observed; potentially as some weak, faint field line movement near the far NE limb around 2025-08-30T03:39Z in SDO AIA 171.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2, but due to the far northern latitude, the longitude range could greatly vary via swpc_cat tool. High confidence in the latitude around N79, though. Half width less than 10 degrees.

note: Wide CME observed first by STEREO A COR2 at 2025-08-30T20:09Z. Updated observations in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 from preliminary analysis where they were not included due to field-of-view with GOES CCOR-1 and a downlink gap resuming at 2025-08-30T21:20Z for SOHO LASCO. The source for this CME is a long duration M2.7 class flare from AR 14199 (N03E13) which began at 2025-08-30T19:11Z and peaked at 2025-08-30T20:02Z, viewed well in SDO AIA 131. Wide field line opening, dimming, and an EUV wave are observed in SDO AIA 131/171/193/211 and GOES SUVI 284. Brightening as a double ribbon flare and post-eruptive arcade observed in SDO AIA 131/171/193/211/304 and GOES SUVI 304. Additionally observed from STEREO A EUVI 195 as field line opening and dimming, and STEREO A EUVI 304 as brightening, around N03E60 as viewed from STEREO A.

cmeAnalyses.note: SHOCK analysis. Well-triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2, with a notably wider half width of 53 degrees.

This analysis is the best fit of the bulk material excluding a southward nose that travels slightly faster than the main front.
PRELIMINARY BULK with single spacecraft STEREO A COR2A only, using the source longitude E13. Awaiting GOES CCOR-1 and SOHO LASCO C2/C3 for triangulation, parameters may vary with updated analysis.

note: Faint CME first seen to the E in STEREO A COR2. It is possibly visible as a tiny amount of brightening to the E in the last couple of frames of running difference imagery of SOHO LASCO C2 before a data gap, but it is not clear enough to determine if it is part of the same feature. The CME is covered by data gap in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and obscured by Earth-shine in GOES CCOR-1. There is not a clearly definitive source for this CME, but a source possibility is some eruptive activity on/over the ENE limb as seen in SDO AIA 304 beginning as early as 2025-08-30T19:30Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement with high degree of uncertainty due to lack of clear source and lack of available triangulation.

note: CME first seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2025-08-31T04:08Z. This CME is also seen for a few frames in STEREO A COR2. This CME does appear in SOHO LASCO C3 and is obscured by Earth-shine in GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is possibly some minor brightening from between AR 14205 and AR 14206 best seen in SDO AIA 304 beginning as early as 2025-08-31T02:00Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Low confidence, best-fit measurement based on imagery from SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 as well as possible visible source.

note: CME first seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2025-08-31T12:48Z. The CME is also seen to the S in GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2. It is very faintly visible for a couple of unmeasurable frames in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this CME is most likely some field line movement from near the S limb best seen in SDO AIA 193, SDO AIA 171, and GOES SUVI 284 beginning around 2025-08-31T10:00Z, possibly related to a small prominence lifting off. Some associated dimming can also be seen in SDO AIA 193. There is also an unlikely possibility that the source is related to eruptive activity from AR 14197. There appears to be some southern and western deflection. This is consistent with the presence of a positive polarity coronal hole in the SE.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best-fit among SOHO LASCO C2, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.

note: CME faintly visible to the NNE in STEREO A COR2 and the N in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. The potential source may be AR 14207 (N30E40), with an eruption characterized by rising loops, best seen in SDO AIA 193/335 starting at 2025-09-02T12:20Z. The eruption is also visible on the limb in STEREO A EUV imagery. Moving field lines can be seen beyond the NE limb in SDO imagery, but the CME was determined to most likely not be farsided.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 as well as potential source location in SWPC_CAT.

note: CME first seen to the NW in STEREO A COR2 starting at 2025-09-03T05:38Z. CME is also seen to NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, but is partially obscured by the pylon. The source of this CME is most likely a filament eruption from the NW quadrant of the Earth-facing disk centered around N30W50. The filament can been seen rising off the disk is SDO AIA 304 beginning around  2025-09-03T00:31Z. The filament eruption can also be seen in STA EUVI 304 slightly N of center disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: Updated bulk measurement based on best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 using backfilled SOHO LASCO imagery that was previously unavailable.
Measurement based on source location and fit in STEREO A COR2.

note: Flux rope CME seen to the NNE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. Source is a streamer blowout.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.

note: Narrow flux rope CME seen to the N in STEREO A COR2 and to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3. Obstructed by the pylon and Earthshine in GOES CCOR-1. Not seen in SOHO LASCO until the end of a data gap in SOHO LASCO at 2025-09-04T06:48Z. Source is likely a C2.9 flare and small eruption with ejecta from N27E10, but with heavy northward deflection, both from AR 14207 seen starting at 2025-09-04T05:25Z in SDO AIA 193. This eruption is in close proximity to a small area of open flux / a small coronal hole centered at N21E09 as seen in SDO AIA 193, which is directly adjacent and to the southwest of AR 14207; this very likely contributed to the strong northwestward deflection of this eruption.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. This measurement is consistent with the heavy northern deflection seen in UV imagery of the source eruption.

note: Faint hight N latitude CME with the likely source a long, very narrow eruption/ejecta in AR 4207 (N28E08) starting at 2025-09-04T10:50Z and going on potentially through 2025-09-04T12Z, and seen in SDO AIA 304, STEREO A EUV 304 and GOES SUVI 304. There is a C2.8 flare from AR 4207 (N30E18) peaking at 2025-09-04T10:55Z likely associated with this CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). This analysis is confirmed by the location of the likely CME source - the narrow northwest directed filament west of AR 4207.

note: Hight northern latitude CME that closely follows and overlaps with the preceding CME: 2025-09-04T13:09Z. Its source is likely the M 1.0-class flare and associated eruption just west of AR 4207 (N28E08) peaking at 2025-09-04T13:44Z as brightening, narrow ejecta going northwestward and dimming in SDO AIA 304, 131, 193, 171, as well as in STEREO A EUV 304 and GOES SUVI 284. The CME seems to deflect northwestwardly, likely because of the minor coronal hole just south of the AR 4207.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). There seems to be significant deflection NW, which can be explained by the effect of a small coronal hole south of the associated AR.

note: CME to the SW seen in GOES CCOR-1 and SOHO LASCO C3 and fully covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2. Its source is a minor eruption at around S40W40 (or 50) seen in AIA 193 as ejecta and a following dimming, with post-eruptive dimming best seen starting around 2025-09-08T18:48Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very uncertain analysis based on the location of the source filament and on the fit with two coronagraphs: SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1.

note: Faint and narrow CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 only. Not visible in SOHO LASCO C3 or GOES CCOR-1 due to faintness of event. Not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap which lasted from 2025-09-04T17:53Z to 2025-09-04T22:08Z. The source may be a small eruption seen as field line movement and possibly a small amount of ejecta emerging from just beyond the W limb, seen starting as early as 2025-09-04T19:27Z at an apparent latitude of N10 in SDO AIA 171/304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement using the three frames of SOHO LASCO C2 in which the CME is visible.

note: A very faint full halo CME best seen to the SE in GOES CCOR-1 and in SOHO LASCO C3. Following SOHO backfill, the CME's start time in SOHO LASCO C2 is closer to 2025-09-04T19:48Z. The CME is completely covered by the large data gap in STEREO A COR2 starting at 2025-09-04T18Z and ending at 2025-09-04T22:08Z. Its source is likely the 2025-09-04T19:19Z central eruption near AR 4206 (N08W09), with a long, narrow southward-directed filament best seen in SDO AIA 304 and in GOES SUVI 304. Dimming and post-eruptive arcades are also best visible in SDO AIA 193, and the eruption can be seen across all wavelengths of SDO AIA imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: UPDATE: Reevaluated to be the SHOCK portion of this CME. Measurement based of fainter, wider, outermost leading edge of the CME.
BULK measurement of the brighter, inner portion of the CME. SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only due to STEREO A COR2 data gap.

A very approximate and unreliable preliminary analysis of the extremely faint and unclear second front of this CME with one coronagraph only (GOES CCOR-1) only. Because the CME is only seen in CCOR-1 and LASCO imagery and not seen in STEREO A COR2 we cannot estimate its width at all.

note: Extremely faint loop CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to faintness of event. Source is uncertain, but may be a set of very narrowly opening field lines seen on the W limb at an apparent latitude of N10, possibly from former AR 14198 (N10W98), starting at 2025-09-04T21:27Z in SDO AIA 171.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2, two frames of SOHO LASCO C3, and three frames of GOES CCOR-1 imagery. Not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to faintness of event.

note: Narrow flux rope CME seen to the NNW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and N in STEREO A COR2. Obstructed by Earthshine in GOES CCOR-1. Source is an eruption centered at N29W05 and an M1.4 flare (N28W00), both from AR 14207 (centered at N29E10). Brightening and ejecta can be seen in SDO AIA 193 starting at 2025-09-05T01:09Z. SDO AIA 304 shows ejecta with heavy northward and slight westward deflection. This eruption is in close proximity to a small coronal hole centered at N21W05 as seen in SDO AIA 193, which is directly adjacent and to the southwest of AR 14207; this very likely contributed to the strong northwestward deflection of this eruption.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2. This eruption is in close proximity to a small coronal hole centered at N21W05 as seen in SDO AIA 193, which is directly adjacent and to the southwest of AR 14207 (centered at N29E10); this very likely contributed to the strong northwestward deflection of this eruption.

note: CME seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. Source is a broad area of brightening, dimming, and subtle opening field lines seen from an area spanning between AR 14207 (N29E07) and AR 14210 (N08E24), centered at N20E20, seen at 2025-09-05T05:00Z in SDO AIA 193/171. Opening field lines from this broad area can be seen very well in STEREO A EUVI 195 at 2025-09-05T05:25Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of STEREO A COR2 and a few frames of SOHO LASCO C2/C3. The leading edge was somewhat visible, but too diffuse to reliably track in GOES CCOR-1.

note: Extremely faint and diffuse CME seen to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 and to the SW in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely on the farside; there is no source discernable in SDO AIA or STEREO A EUVI imagery, and triangulation suggests a farsided source location.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using a few frames of SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2. The leading edge was somewhat visible, but too diffuse to reliably track in GOES CCOR-1.

note: Faint CME seen to the East in SOHO LASCO C2 only. Source is uncertain; there is no clear source in available UV imagery of the disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement taken using frames of SOHO LASCO C2.

note: Jet-like CME to the N/NE in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, GOES CCOR-1, STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is filament ejecta visible beyond the NE limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-09-06T09:32Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on best fit using SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: Bright wide CME observed to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source is partially filament ejecta, partial rising loop. In SDO AIA 171/304, a long filament spanning the S and SW disk at high southern latitudes is agitated around 2025-09-06T06:35Z, kicks up more around 2025-09-06T09:56Z, and around 2025-09-06T11:26Z a rising loop further on/around west limb lifts off appearing to take some filament material with it although the full filament stays mostly in-tact.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.

note: CME observed to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The source for this CME is associated with the cluster of active regions on the west limb, observed as a wide, slow loop rising and wide field line breaking/dimming starting as early as 2025-09-06T11:00Z and more explosively around 2025-09-06T14:45Z in SDO AIA 171/193, better observed in the wider field-of-view of GOES SUVI 284/304 due to the width of eruption. There is a concurrent small filament eruption near AR 14206 (~N08W32) at 2025-09-06T14:48Z, however triangulation of the CME fronts in coronagraphs strongly lean towards the west limb source.

cmeAnalyses.note: SHOCK analysis. Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C3 only, and STEREO A COR2.

BULK analysis. Triangulated measurement betweeen SOHO LASCO C3 only, and STEREO A COR2. Leading edge is dimpled and diffuse, so some uncertainty lies in the longitude and could range W95-W115, but good confidence in the far-sided west limb.

note: Faint CME observed to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 as a pileup of a few outflowing concentric fronts following larger CME 2025-09-06T13:25Z. No distinct source is seen in SDO AIA or GOES SUVI for this material, but in coronagraph imagery it triangulates well in the same direction as CME 2025-09-06T13:25Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between STEREO A COR2 and only later frames of SOHO LASCO C3 due to the evolving CME shape through the coronagraphs being difficult to track in LASCO C2.

note: Faint outflow CME to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2, C3, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Not clearly visible in GOES CCOR-1. No clear source, but likely associated with restructuring following large CME eruptions to the W/SW starting at 2025-09-06T13:36Z through 16:48Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Parameters based on best fit. Higher uncertainty due to diffuse leading edge.

note: A very faint CME directed to the south in SOHO LASCO (C2 and C3) and GOES CCOR-1 and to the southwest in STEREO A COR2. No source for this event has been found, but there is some repeated flaring in the Active Region close to the southwest limb as seen from STEREO A EUVI 195 at the time.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). Analysis indicates that this is a far-side event. It is not confirmed by the source, which was not found and is likely on the far side.

note: CME with a brighter narrower bulk and a wide faint shock front to the south in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1. It is directed to the SSW in STEREO A COR2. There is a data gap in C2 covering the start of this CME, so the actual start time can be a bit earlier. No clear source has been found in EUV imagery, but there is a faint movement of field lines in the SSW in SDO AIA 171 after 2025-09-07T19:00Z, which could possibly be indicating a far-sided eruption.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximage analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). The source has not been found in EUV imagery and is likely far-sided.

note: Faint CME observed to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and the SSE in STEREO A COR2. The source is a small filament on-disk at high southern latitudes, faint to see before eruption but appears to span ~S65W03 to ~S65W30 with some uncertainty. Eruption begins around 2025-09-08T04:00Z and observed as rising filament material in SDO AIA 304 and breaking field lines in SDO AIA 171/193.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

note: Far-sided CME observed well to the W in STEREO A COR2, and as a faint far-sided halo in GOES CCOR-1 although the faint edge and pylon obscure this from view in CCOR-1 running difference imagery. Not observed yet in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 due to a data gap. The source is not observed in SDO AIA or GOES SUVI due to the far-sided longitude, but Solar Orbiter EUI and STIX instruments help estimate the longitude to likely be around W150-W170. Peaking at 2025-09-08T10:25Z, low latency Solar Orbiter STIX observed an estimated GOES class M2 [M1,M3 C.I.] near the NE limb as viewed from Solar Orbiter, which is located at heliographic longitude E128 at this time. Low latency Solar Orbiter EUI 174/304 has an available frame at 2025-09-08T08:06Z, observing a bright region in the NE as viewed from Solar Orbiter around W150-W170 which may be former AR 14191.

cmeAnalyses.note: STEREO A COR2 only 3D measurement, as it is too faint in GOES CCOR-1 running difference imagery and not in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 yet due to a data gap. Longitude could easily range W150-W170 with the estimated location using low latency Solar Orbiter STIX and EUI instruments.

STEREO A COR2 only 3D measurement, as it is too faint in GOES CCOR-1 running difference imagery and not in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 yet due to a data gap. Longitude could easily range W150-W170 with the estimated location using low latency Solar Orbiter STIX and EUI instruments.

note: CME first seen to the North in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-09009T03:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This vent is obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. The source of this is a C1.5 flare and minor jet-like eruption beginning at approximately 2025-09-09T03:14Z stemming from AR 14207 (N27W50) seen exhibiting a strong Northwestern deflection in SDO AIA 304 and 171.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

note: Partial halo CME first seen to the West by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-09-09T12:38Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a flare and instance of wide opening field lines beginning at approximately 2025-09-09T11:55Z seen along the Western limb (approx. N10W130) in STEREO A EUVI 195. Field line opening is also visible on the West limb in SDO AIA 193. This activity may stem from former Active Region 14199 which was responsible for numerous M-class flares while on the Earth facing disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: BULK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1.
SHOCK measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1.

note: CME first seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-09-09T15:00Z. This CME is also seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 but is obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. There is no clear source on the Earth-facing disk. This front is most likely continued outflow following CME: 2025-09-09T12:38Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best-fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

note: Narrow jet CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, and extremely faintly to the NW in STEREO A COR2. Source is the eruption of a small filament spanning from N10 to N15 and from W65 to W75 starting at 2025-09-09T16:33Z as seen in SDO AIA 304. This eruption is also seen in SDO AIA 193/171, GOES SUVI 304/284, and in STEREO A EUVI 304/195. There is also a narrow jet of ejecta seen at N28W60 from AR 14207, directly north of the filament, which begins erupting slightly earlier, starting around 2025-09-09T16:03Z as seen in SDO AIA 304/171 and at 2025-09-09T16:15Z as seen in STEREO A EUVI 304, but the parameters of the triangulated fit is in better agreement with the small filament eruption as the source.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

note: An extremely faint loop CME only seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery and not seen in C3 and GOES CCOR-1. No clear source for this CME has been found indicating that the source is likely far-sided. The source might be indicated by some - rather unclear - but possible movement of field lines on/just behind the west limb in STEREO A EUV 193 imagery after 2025-09-10T01:00Z. A far-sided (behind the limb in STEREO A) source is corroborated by the speculative triangulated measurement of this front.

cmeAnalyses.note: A very speculative analysis based on the fit of an extremely faint front with SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs. No clear source has been found but the fit suggest that the source is far-sided, behind the west limb as seen from STEREO A.

note: Narrow jet-like CME to the NNW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3; not seen in any other coronagraph. It is likely obscured by pylon in GOES CCOR-1 and it is possible that it is going almost directly (although to the north) at the observer in STEREO A and hence is not seen in this coronagraph. Its source is a minor eruption in AR 14207 (N27W63) seen around 2025-09-10T09:19Z, with a narrow, long ejecta best seen in GOES SUVI 304 at 2025-09-10T10:01Z but also seen in SDO AIA 131/304, and in STEREO A EUVI 195 as dimming. The ejecta and the CME seem to deflect northward. The CME is likely associated with the C1.3 flare from AR 14207 (N25W65) peaking at 2025-09-10T09:25Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate single-coronagraph analysis (with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 coronagraph) based on the location of the CME source (a narrow ejecta from AR 14207). The CME is not seen in GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2. The CME is clearly deflecting northward.

note: Faint loop CME first seen to the SE in STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-09-10T14:38Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. This event is blocked by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. There is no clear source seen for this event, aside from some very minor field line movement seen along the SE limb in SDO AIA 171 beginning at approx. 2025-09-10T13:41Z. This CME is overtaken by CME: 2025-09-10T17:09Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit between STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1.

note: Faint loop CME first seen to the SE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-09-10T17:09Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. This event is blocked by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. There is no clear source seen for this event, but some minor field line movement is visible along the SE limb in SDO AIA 171 beginning at approx. 2025-09-10T16:41Z. This CME overtakes previous CME, CME: 2025-09-10T14:38Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit between STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1.

note: Thin CME observed to the NNW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2, obscured by the pylon and earthshine in GOES CCOR-1. The source is likely a small filament ejecta deflecting northward from AR 14207 observed in SDO AIA 171/193/304, associated with a C1.1 flare which peaked at 2025-09-11T03:27Z. The flare had two bright points in SDO AIA 131 at N26W75 and N28W85, the former being the brightest spot and the latter where the filament ejecta launches from and thus is marked as the CME location here.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. CME half width is less than 10 degrees.

note: Narrow CME to the N (high northern latitude). The source is a narrow ejecta from AR 14207 seen at 2025-09-11T06:25Z especially well in GOES SUVI 304 but also in SDO AIA 304. The ejecta seems to deflect northward, as all recent CMEs/ejecta from this AR, likely because of a small coronal hole just to the S of the AR. There is an associated C1.4 flare from this AR peaking at 2025-09-11T06:26Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs and confirmed by the source (flare to the W of AR 14207). The CME seems to deflect northward, just as the associated ejecta seen in EUV imagery. Deflection is likely due to the small coronal hole just south of this Active Region.

note: Narrow CME seen to the SE in STEREO A COR2 closely following the fainter CME: 2025-09-11T07:53Z. It is seen as a faint, asymmetrical and messy partial halo to the SSE in SOHO LASCO C2. The source is likely the complex eruption of a southern filament mostly seen in SDO AIA 193 as a faint dimming and ejecta and lasting/developing for hours. The filament seems to be centered very approximately around S40E05 but the filament stretches (mostly along latitude) at least from S40E45 to S30W05. There is also a more western, fainter, feature of this CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 but it is hard to fit in the analysis. There are also potential one or two follow-up fronts in coronagraphs following this CME.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate analysis of the complex front based on the fit with SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 coronagraphs, and on the location of the source eruption.

Approximate initial analysis with early imagery based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2) and on the source (eruption of the southern filament). There might be a bit of a northern deflection from the latitude of the source (S35-40).

note: Faint CME with a fuzzy front to the E seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1 but not seen in other coronagraphs. Its source is likely behind the E limb (there are moving field lines, possibly post-eruptive arcades there starting after ~2025-09-11T09Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Because the CME is only seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1 and is not seen in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph, and its source has not been found, it is only possible to make aplane-of-sky measurement of this event.

note: CME visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Not visible in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely in the vicinity of Active Region 14216, located at approximately N10W90, but the source eruption is not clearly visible on the disk in available EUV imagery. Moving field lines are seen in SDO AIA 171/193 and an eruption of material is seen on the east limb in GOES SUVI 304 starting around 2025-09-11T16:05Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on potential source location on the limb. The longitude is approximate and may vary by approximately +/- 10 degrees. The leading edge of the CME fades away quickly in running difference imagery and is not measurable beyond a few frames of SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1.

note: Faint and narrow CME first seen to the NNW in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-09-12T00:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This CME is obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is a minor eruption of material from AR 14207 (N29W85) exhibiting Northern deflection beginning at approx. 2025-09-11T23:48Z in SDO AIA 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and few available frames of CME before front fades. CME exhibits a strong Northern deflection.

note: Faint and hazy CME first seen to the NE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-09-12T03:53Z, as well as to the North in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. This event is not clearly visible in GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is continued dimming and field line movement seen in SDO AIA 193 and 211 centered at approx. N50E15 following a large filament eruption which left the disk at approx. 2025-09-11T22:18Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

note: Faint CME observed to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. The source is a small filament eruption likely from former AR 14212 now around the west limb as viewed from SDO AIA and GOES SUVI, but viewed directly in STEREO A EUVI. Narrow filament ejecta and field line movement over the west limb best observed in GOES SUVI 284/304 starting around 2025-09-12T02:53Z is also observed in SDO AIA 171/193/304. Brightening at the location of former AR 14212 as viewed from STEREO A in EUVI 195 at 2025-09-12T03:05Z and EUVI 304 at 2025-09-12T03:15Z are also observed for a single frame due to the instrument's lower cadence.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2 of the brighest piece of this faint front, the outermost leading edge is too faint and diffuse to track. Front becomes too faint after earliest frames.

note: Faint CME observed to the E in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, it is faintly identifiable in STEREO A COR2 white light but not trackable in running difference imagery. No direct source for this CME is observed on-disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only due to lack of visiblity in STEREO A COR2 running difference imagery and no observed on-disk source.

note: Faint, narrow CME first seen to the NNW in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-09-12T06:24Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This event is obscured by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is a minor eruption of material from AR 14207 (N28W89) exhibiting Northern deflection beginning at approx. 2025-09-12T05:38Z in SDO AIA 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2.

note: CME first seen to the SW in STEREO A COR2 starting at 2025-09-12T15:09Z. CME is also seen to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. The source of this CME is a far-sided filament eruption near the western limb from the perspective of STEREO A. The filament can be seen in STA EUVI 304 starting to rise around 2025-09-12T13:15Z, erupting off the disk later around 2025-09-12T14:15Z. The filament eruption is also observed in STA EUVI 195. In addition, the prominence can be seen around the SW limb in SDO AIA 131/171/193/304 and GOES SUVI 284/304 starting around 2025-09-12T14:31Z accompanied by field line movement and an EUV wave.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best-fit among SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 as well as visible far-sided source.

note: CME first seen to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2025-09-12T17:24Z. CME is also visible to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The is most likely additional outflow following filament eruption CME: 2025-0912T15:09Z as no independent source has been found, and the measured source location matches that of CME: 2025-09-12T15:09Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best-fit among SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1.

note: Faint and narrow CME seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Not discernable in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to faintness, and possibly directionality, of this event. Source is likely material seen leaving from beyond the WNW limb, at an apparent latitude of N15, starting as early as 2025-09-12T23:22Z in SDO AIA 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement of faint leading edge using SOHO LASCO C2/C3. This CME becomes diffuse after two frames of SOHO LASCO C3. This CME becomes diffuse after one frame of GOES CCOR-1. Not discernable in STEREO A COR2 imagery due to faintness, and possibly directionality, of event.

note: Narrow flux rope CME seen to the South in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Not discernable in STEREO A COR2. Source is a very gradual filament eruption, with movement of filamentary material seen in SDO AIA 304 starting around 2025-09-13T01:21Z, and with full liftoff seen at about 2025-09-13T06:27Z. The filament extends from about S20E30 to S20W00, and erupts with southward deflection. This filament eruption can also be seen in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery on the East/Southeast limb of STEREO A, gradually lifting off from about 2025-09-13T00:15Z to 2025-09-13T06:15Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 imagery. Although this eruption was visible in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery on the East limb of STEREO A, the CME is not discernable in STEREO A COR2.

note: Loop CME seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. CME is not discernable in STEREO A COR2, likely due to faintness and directionality of this event. Source is a gradually rising loop seen on or just beyond the East limb and spanning from about S10 to S20 in SDO AIA 171 starting as early as 2025-09-13T07:03Z, but with full liftoff seen around 2025-09-13T08:12Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, which is likely very close to the true parameters due to the source location being on or just beyond the East limb.

note: Faint CME to the NW in all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). Its source is seen in STEREO A EUV imagery as a faint ejecta around 12:15Z (and faintly in GOES SUVI 304 at 2025-09-13T12:17Z), and as minor post-eruptive arcades close to the NW limb in STEREO A (~N10W70 as seen from STEREO), starting around 2025-09-13T11:45Z - likely the eruption from the former AR 14207 (which should be at the longitude of ~115 deg at the time of the eruptions).

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the source location as seen in STEREO A EUVI 304/195 and on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2).

note: Faint, relatively narrow CME to the NW in all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1), following CME: 2025-09-13T12:12Z (C2). The front is fuzzy. The source is likely the faint ejecta seen off the NW limb in STEREO A EUV 304 at 2025-09-13T13:15Z and also in GOES SUVI 304 at 2025-09-13T13:21Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1) and confirmed by the location of the likely source (former AR 14207).

note: A very faint narrow jet-like CME seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Not visible in STEREO A COR2. No clear source has been found.

cmeAnalyses.note: Since we do not see this CME in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph, only POS analysis is possible.

note: A very narrow jet-like CME to the NW mostly seen in SOHO LASCO C2 running difference imagery and in a few early timestamps of C3. It's source is possibly a very narrow minor ejecta likely from AR 14207 going directly northward just before 2025-09-13T17Z, as seen in GOES SUVI 304 and (fainter) in STEREO A EUV 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Since we do not see this CME in any other coronagraph other than SOHO LASCO and the source is behind the limb (possibly AR 14207), only plane-of-sky analysis is definitive.

note: Faint jet-like CME to the SSW in SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1 running difference imagery, not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2. Its source could be a minor eruption close to the SSW limb seen in STEREO A EUV 304 around 2025-09-14T05:15Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Because the CME is only seen in SOHO LASCO C2 and GOES CCOR-1 and not clearly seen in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph and the source location is not exactly clear, only plane-of-sky analysis is possible.

note: Loop CME to the E in SOHO LASCO C2/GOES CCOR-1/STEREO A COR2. Source is likely the wide opening/restructuring of field lines to the E in GOES SUVI 195/284 after 2025-09-14T08:30Z, followed by post-eruptive arcades peeking from behind the E limb, likely from the yet unnumbered AR behind the ESE limb (possibly former AR 4197). Additionally, there is a possible candidate eruption of a mid-size filament centered ~(S05E70) seen in GOES SUVI 304 starting at 2025-09-14T09:17Z, accompanied by a significant area dimming in the SE quadrant, mostly to the N of the unnumbered plage area at (~S15E60). There was also lower C class flaring on/behind the SE limb, possibly associated with these eruptions.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). The source seems to be far-sided/behind the E limb.

note: Bright, wide asymmetrical partial halo to the NE in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1, with two asymmetrical lobes (the northern one seemingly a bit faster initially) and a dimpled front. The CME is seen directly north in STEREO A COR2 coronagraph, so it is clearly a far-sided event. The start of this event could be even a bit earlier but it seems to get increase in speed around 2025-09-14T12Z. Coronal signatures include restructuring of magnetic field behind the NE limb around 2025-09-14T11:59Z, as seen in GOES SUVI 284 and 195, however there is also some minor dimming in the NE on the visible, Earth-facing disk (in GOES SUVI 195) around the same time.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). The source seems to be far-sided, based on the coronal signatures (restructuring of magnetic field behind the NE limb in GOES SUVI). Only two STEREO A COR2 images were available for this analysis.

note: Faint CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-09-14T20:12Z, as well as by GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap beginning at 2025-09-14T18:09Z, and is directed into the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this event is field line opening seen along the SE limb (approx. S25E90) in GOES SUVI 195 beginning at approx. 2025-09-14T19:14Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement due to source near the limb and lack of STEREO A COR2 to triangulate. Longitudes fitting between approx. -105 and -80.

note: Faint loop CME seen to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1; SSW in STEREO A COR2. Source is uncertain, but may be some opening field lines seen beyond the South limb in GOES SUVI 284 around 2025-09-15T01:20Z. Subtle opening field lines are also seen on the S/SW limb of STEREO A EUVI 195 starting as early as 2025-09-15T00:55Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using several frames of SOHO LASCO C3, a few frames of STEREO A COR2, and a few frames of GOES CCOR-1. STEREO A COR2 imagery was at a reduced cadence at the time of this eruption.

note: Faint, diffuse CME seen to the East in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. Source is opening field lines seen on the East limb in GOES SUVI 284 starting around 2025-09-13T01:15Z. Eruption is also seen as opening field lines and brightening seen on the NE limb in STEREO A EUVI 195 starting around 2025-09-15T01:35Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement using frames of SOHO LASCO C2/C3, two frames of STEREO A COR2, and two frames of GOES CCOR-1. STEREO A COR2 was at a reduced cadence due to a campaign.

note: Jet CME seen to the NNW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Obstructed by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. Source is likely one of two narrow eruptions from a region seen on the STEREO A northwest limb (W137 from Earth's perspective), both at N20 and with strong northward deflection, possibly from former AR 14207 which would have been located at approx. N27W135 at the time of these candidate eruptions. The first eruption candidate eruption can be seen as a narrow jet of ejecta in STEREO A EUVI 304 at 2025-09-15T04:15Z. The second candidate eruption can be seen from the same location, but occurring slightly later at 2025-09-15T05:15Z in STEREO A EUVI 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Best fit measurement of the faint leading edge using the candidate source location and several frames of SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and two frames of STEREO A COR2. Obstructed by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. STEREO A COR2 imagery was at a reduced cadence at the time of this eruption.

note: Extremely faint and diffuse CME seen to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2. Source is uncertain; there is no clear source in available UV imagery of the disk.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement using a few frames of SOHO LASCO C2.

note: CME first seen to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-09-16T04:24Z. CME is also seen to the SE in GOES CCOR-1 and STEREO A COR2 and is mostly obscured by the pylon in SOHO LASCO C3. The source of this CME is a large filament eruption near/beyond the SE limb. The prominence can be seen starting to rise off the disk as early as 2025-09-16T00:00Z and "snaps" around 2025-09-16T04:01Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best-fit among SOHO LASCO C2, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 as well as visible source.

note: CME first seen to the E in SOHO LASCO C2 starting around 2025-09-16T04:36Z and can also faintly be seen for a couple of frames in SOHO LASCO C3. This CME is not visible in STEREO A COR2 or GOES CCOR-1. There is no definite source for this CME; the source is most likely far-sided.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement based on running difference imagery from SOHO LASCO C2 and a couple frames from SOHO LASCO C3.

note: Faint CME observed to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and best in STEREO A COR2. The source is likely a complex slow eruption from AR 4223 observed in GOES SUVI 284/304 as field line loop rising/movement starting as early as 2025-09-16T12:24Z. This slow eruption may also be responsible for similar CMEs including slower, concurrent CME 2025-09-16T15:36Z and slightly later CME 2025-09-16T17:36Z, which share similar triangulation and source observation/timing.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulated measurement with SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2, CME becomes too faint within LASCO C2 and a STEREO A COR2 data gap begins at 2025-09-17T17:08Z after which the CME is not visible.

note: Faint CME observed to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and one frame of STEREO A COR2 at 2025-09-16T17:08Z before a data gap. The source is likely a complex slow eruption from AR 4223 observed in GOES SUVI 284/304 as field line loop rising/movement starting as early as 2025-09-16T12:24Z. This slow eruption may also be responsible for similar CMEs including slower, concurrent CME 2025-09-16T15:36Z and slightly later CME 2025-09-16T17:36Z, which share similar triangulation and source observation/timing.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulated measurement with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and a single frame of STEREO A COR2 at 2025-09-16T17:08Z due to a data gap after which the CME is not visible. Triangulation assisted by GOES SUVI source observations.

note: Faint CME observed to the ESE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. The source is a complex slow eruption from AR 4223 observed in GOES SUVI 284/304 as field line loop rising/movement starting as early as 2025-09-16T12:24Z, with a secondary larger piece starting at 2025-09-16T14:24Z which reaches the edge of the GOES SUVI field-of-view around 2025-09-16T15:56Z and is the more likely candidate here. The first piece of this eruption may be observed as additional faint CME fronts beginning at 2025-09-16T15:12Z / 2025-09-16T15:36Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulated measurement between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. Reduced data cadence in STEREO A COR2 and diffuse CME front increases uncertainty, but the longitude likely ranges ~E70-E80 based on concurrent GOES SUVI observations.

note: Hazy CME first seen to the SE by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-09-17T00:48Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is field line movement tracing back to a small eruption from near Active Region 14223 (S10E55) as seen in GOES SUVI 195 beginning at approx. 2025-09-21:12Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1.

note: Faint CME with hazy front first seen in the NE by STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-09-17T13:23Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This CME is too faint to be seen clearly in GOES CCOR-1. The source of this event is field line opening seen along the NE limb in GOES SUVI 195 beginning at approximately 2025-09-17T12:40Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

note: CME first seen to the East in STEREO A COR2 beginning at 2025-09-17T14:23Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C2/C3 in later frames. The source of this event is field line opening seen along or just beyond the East limb in STEREO A EUVI 195 beginning at approx. 2025-09-17T12:55Z, signaling that this event is fully far sided with respect to Earth.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1. The front of this CME is faint and difficult to track in GOES CCOR-1 and unable to be tracked in SOHO LASCO C3.

note: Faint CME visible to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, not clearly visible in GOES CCOR-1 or STEREO A COR2. The source is unclear is available EUV imagery, and may be farsided.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane of sky measurement using SOHO LASCO C2/C3 running difference imagery in SWPC_CAT.

note: CME faintly visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1. The potential source is an eruption west of AR 14225, around approximately N15E50, best seen as dimming in GOES SUVI 195 starting at approximately 2025-09-17T16:00Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery in SWPC_CAT as well as potential source location.

note: Faint minor CME first seen to the W in SOHO LASCO C2 starting at 2025-09-18T05:48Z. This CME is also seen in STEREO A COR2 but not in SOHO LASCO C3 or GOES CCOR-1. There is no clear source on the Earth-facing disk. The source is likely far-sided which is consistent with measurement.

cmeAnalyses.note: A very approximate analysis based on the fit of this faint fuzzy front in SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs. No source has been found in EUV imagery to confirm parameters.

note: Faint front only seen in early imagery of SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. It closely follows 2025-09-18T5:48Z CME. No source for it has been found, so it is likely far-sided.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate analysis based on the fit with two coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2) and not confirmed by source (which has not been found).

note: A wide, asymmetrical, slanted front - a likely partial halo in SOHO LASCO - which follows the 2025-09-18T08:45Z CME. It is seen in all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1), and is wider and more like a partial halo in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 than in COR2, where it is fainter and narrower. No clear source found for this CME but there is an extremely faint possible movement of field lines behind the W limb in STEREO A EUV 195 and 304 after 2025-09-18T10:30Z.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very uncertain analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). The longitude could be lower (~135 deg.)

note: Minor CME seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2A associated with a large fan-like filament erupting in Active Region 14225 (N10E60) starting at 2025-09-18T15:00Z, as seen in GOES SUVI 304 and on or just behind the east limb in STEREO EUVI A 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge measurement mainly relying on imagery in STEREO A COR2A but with SOHO LASCO C2 data up to 2025-09-18T16:24Z.

note: Second of two CMEs seen to the northeast in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2A which appears to be associated with a large fan-like filament erupting in Active Region 14225 (N10E60) starting at 2025-09-18T15:00Z, as seen in GOES SUVI 304 and on or just behind the east limb in STEREO EUVI A 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: Leading edge measurement using STEREO A COR2 and SOHO C2 for triangulation; some eastward deflection was noted in the leading edge relative to the supposed source.

note: CME observed to the E in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. The southern half of this feature is notably brighter, but the initially asymmetric front evens out further into the coronagraphs. The source appears to be far-sided around the equatorial east limb, only observed as some field line movement starting around 2025-09-18T22:42Z in GOES SUVI 171.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2.

note: CME observed to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR. This CME has no observable source in GOES SUVI or STEREO A EUVI. The CME front appears to materialize close to the occulting disk in LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 and widen as it travels.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C3 and STEREO A COR2 using later frames only, as the CME front shape widens and changes shape in early COR2A and LASCO C2 frames.

note: Faint CME observed to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2. No distinct source is observed for this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: Triangulation between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 with early frames as the diffuse front is difficult to track beyond this.

note: A very faint fuzzy front only seen in a few timestamps of SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 to the NE in both coronagraphs, with possibly a couple of timestamps in SOHO LASCO C3 and GOES CCOR-1. There are multiple faint fronts before and after this one, so any analysis is very speculative. There is a very faint movement/opening of field lines on/behind the NE limb seen around 2025-09-19T23:30Z in GOES SUVI 284 imagery but the fit between coronagraphs indicated an on-disk longitude.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with SOHO LASCO and STEREO A COR2 coronagraphs. No clear source has been found for this CME.

note: Extremely faint narrow CME to the S in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1 and SSE in STEREO A COR2. No clear source has been found.

cmeAnalyses.note: Approximate analysis based on the fit with three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). No source has been found to confirm parameters.

note: Extremely faint CME following 2025-09-20T00:48Z CME and seen in the S in LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 and to the SE in STEREO A COR2. No clear source found in EUV imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate analysis based on the fit of the faint fuzzy front with 3 coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). No source found to confirm these parameters.

note: Narrow, diffuse CME first seen to the East in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-09-21T02:48Z, as well as faintly by STEREO A COR2 in later frames. This CME is only visible for a few frames in STEREO A COR2 due to a reduced, 1-hour cadence, and is not visible in SOHO LASCO C3 or GOES CCOR-1 due to faintness. There is no clear source seen for this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky measurement due to uncertain source location and lack of available coronagraph imagery to triangulate.

note: Narrow, very faint, jet-like CME seen SSE in all 3 coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1) but only for a few timestamps, after which it becomes too faint. Its front is fuzzy and not clear in all timestamps. No clear source has been found for this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: A very uncertain analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). No source has been found for this CME in available EUV imagery to confirm this analysis.

note: Faint loop CME seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO (and possibly to the N in STEREO A COR2 in one timestamp before data gap). It is likely completely covered by a data gap in STEREO A and is covered by the pylon in GOES CCOR-1. It is better seen in running difference imagery. Its source is a large loop-like prominence that gradually develops on/behind the NW limb as seen from GOES SUVI starting after 2025-09-21T19Z (in GOES SUVI 304). The filament eruption is also seen close to the NW limb in STEREO A EUVI 304 and 195 around (N30W70, very approximately).

cmeAnalyses.note: Updated measurement including STEREO A COR2A imagery.
Speculative analysis with one coronagraph (SOHO LASCO), based on the very approximate source location (as seen in STEREO A EUVI close to the NW limb).

note: Faint asymmetrical CME with an irregular front to the NE with the start time that could be even earlier. The CME overlaps with a NE streamer making analysis more difficult. Source is likely a large prominence eruption seen in GOES SUVI 304 and STEREO A EUV 304, slowly developing close to the NE limb (very approx. ~N50E70) after 2025-09-21T19Z and having two distinct lobes, with the more eastern lobe possibly falling back into corona.

cmeAnalyses.note: Very approximate  Analysis based on the fit with all three coronagraphs (SOHO LASCO, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1). There seems to be a bit of a westward deflection from the source location.

note: A relatively bright jet-like CME seen to the ESE in SOHO LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 coronagraph and covered by the data gap in STEREO A COR2. No clear source has been found, however there is some activity on the E limb as seen in GOES SUVI 304.

cmeAnalyses.note: The CME is covered by a data gap in STEREO A COR2, so only LASCO and GOES CCOR-1 imagery is available for it. No clear source has been found for this event. Only plane-of-sky analysis is possible.

note:
Bright light-bulb shaped CME to the SW in SOHO LASCO, with the start covered by the data gap in STEREO A COR2 (the gap starts right before the CME start).
The source is a large prominence from behind the SW limb in GOES SUVI 304 and in the SW quadrant, not far from the SW limb in STEREO A EUV 304 and 195. The filament is centered around (S35W50) as seen from STEREO A, so around (S35W97) as we would see from Earth.

cmeAnalyses.note: Updated measurement with additional imagery.

note: This CME has a diffuse, faint leading edge but is visible to the east in SOHO LASCO C2, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. It is not observed in SOHO LASCO C3 imagery as it is blocked by the pylon. The source is likely related to an opening of field lines observed over the eastern limb starting around 2025-09-22T06:30Z as seen in GOES SUVI 171, 195, 284 imagery. Additionally, there is minor brightening centered near S05E45 which may be related to the opening of field lines.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery.

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. The source is likely far-sided as there are no source signatures visible on the Earth-facing disk around the time of this event.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C3, GOES CCOR-1, and STEREO A COR2 imagery. As the source is likely far-sided, a precise source location is unknown. The measured parameters may vary slightly as a result.

note: CME observed to the NE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1, not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. The source is a filament eruption observed near the NE limb which begins to lift off around 2025-09-22T14:30Z seen in GOES SUVI 171/195/304, which appears likely far-sided by the lack of on-disk brightening underneath the eruption. Post-eruptive arcade loops are faintly seen over the limb following the eruption, as well as by Solar Orbiter EUI 304 located at approx. N25E105.

cmeAnalyses.note: SOHO LASCO C3 only plane-of-sky as the CME front is more uniform by C3 FOV, and no STEREO A COR2 is available to triangulate how far-sided this source longitude is. Longitude fits range from approx. E125 and E80.

note: Bright loop CME first seen to the NW in SOHO LASCO C2 beginning 2025-09-22T21:36Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1. The source is rising field clearly over the far-sided NW limb, slowly starting ~18Z, more prominently visible starting 2025-09-22T20:35Z in SUVI 284.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and COR2A.

note: CME first seen in the SW by SOHO LASCO C2 beginning at 2025-09-23T00:12Z, as well as by SOHO LASCO C3, STEREO A COR2 and GOES CCOR-1 in later frames. The source of this event is a filament eruption seen beginning at approx. 2025-09-22T22:40Z from beyond the SW limb in GOES SUVI 304, and along the SW limb in STEREO A EUVI 304. Field line opening can also be seen in GOES SUVI 195.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on approximate source location and best fit between SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and STEREO A COR2. There is no GOES CCOR-1 imagery for this event due to an eclipse.

note: Faint CME observed to the SE in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. Not observed in STEREO A COR2 due to a data gap. No observable source is seen in GOES SUVI or STEREO A EUVI imagery.

cmeAnalyses.note: Plane-of-sky with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 as STEREO A COR2 not available due to a data gap and no eruption source is observed. CME is less than 10 HW.

note: Thin CME observed to the SW in SOHO LASCO C2/C3 and GOES CCOR-1. This CME is not observed in STEREO A COR2, but it is a thin CME pointed almost directly at STEREO A (~W47.8 at this time) so it may be obscured by the occulting disk. The source may be a small brightening around S15W52 near AR 14217 beginning around 2025-09-23T22:52Z in GOES SUVI 171/195, with some field line movement extending over the SW limb at this time.

cmeAnalyses.note: Single spacecraft 3D measurement with SOHO LASCO C2/C3 only due to no visibility in STEREO A COR2, using the observed source near S15W52 as the basis and finding a good fit at these parameters.

note: This CME is visible to the southwest in SOHO LASCO C2/C3, STEREO A COR2, and GOES CCOR-1 coronagraphs. The source is obscured by an eclipse in GOES SUVI imagery, but there is minor brightening observed around 2025-09-24T04:15Z from Active Region 14217 (S16W50) in STEREO A EUVI 304 imagery. However, it is also possible this event is far-sided due to the uncertainty in the observed source.

cmeAnalyses.note: Measurement based on the best fit between SOHO LASCO C2 and STEREO A COR2 imagery. Due to uncertainty in the source location, the measured parameters may vary slightly.
